{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534525"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:47:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:47:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14982"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14982"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.7,0.05,0.07,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7670"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59675"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7670"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14982"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45087"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"1366"},{"type":"tags","id":"3516"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5188"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18749"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59675"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit following a motor vehicle accident. She has a history of bipolar disorder and hypertension. Her regular medications include lithium, venlafaxine, and perindopril. In addition to her regular medications, she is currently intubated and sedated on a fentanyl and propofol infusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn day three of admission, she develops hypernatraemia with a sodium of 152 mmol/L (135-145). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears clinically euvolaemic. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her fluid balance chart shows appropriate oral and intravenous fluid replacement. Her urine output is noted to be 4.5 L over the past 24 hours.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely causing the hypernatraemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Venlafaxine","Lithium","Fentanyl","Perindopril","Propofol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has developed hypernatraemia with polyuria while in ICU, suggesting diabetes insipidus. Among the medications listed, \u003Cstrong\u003Elithium\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause as it is well-known to cause nephrogenic diabetes insipidus by interfering with aquaporin-2 water channels in the collecting duct, leading to an inability to concentrate urine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E, an ACE inhibitor, does not typically cause hypernatraemia. In fact, it may occasionally cause hyponatraemia through its effects on aldosterone suppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenlafaxine\u003C/strong\u003E, a serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor, has been associated with syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH) which causes hyponatraemia, not hypernatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFentanyl\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Epropofol \u003C/strong\u003Einfusions do not directly affect sodium or water homeostasis and are not typically associated with hypernatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELithium-induced nephrogenic diabetes insipidus occurs in up to 40% of patients on long-term lithium therapy. The mechanism involves downregulation of aquaporin-2 expression in the collecting duct, leading to resistance to antidiuretic hormone (ADH). This results in the inability to concentrate urine, causing polyuria and subsequent hypernatraemia if fluid replacement is inadequate. The condition may persist even after lithium discontinuation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lithium causes nephrogenic diabetes insipidus by interfering with aquaporin-2 channels in the collecting duct.","Common medications causing hypernatraemia in ICU include lithium, mannitol, and loop diuretics.","Hypernatraemia in ICU patients requires careful evaluation of medication history and fluid balance."],"references":["Ott M, Forss\u00e9n B, Werneke U. Lithium treatment, nephrogenic diabetes insipidus and the risk of hypernatraemia: a retrospective cohort study. Ther Adv Psychopharmacol. 2019 Apr 4;9:2045125319836563. doi: 10.1177/2045125319836563. PMID: 31007893; PMCID: PMC6457074.","Liamis G, Milionis HJ, Elisaf M. A review of drug-induced hypernatraemia. NDT Plus. 2009 Oct;2(5):339-46. doi: 10.1093/ndtplus/sfp085. Epub 2009 Jul 16. PMID: 25949338; PMCID: PMC4421386."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45087"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14982"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45087"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-08T16:17:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-08T16:18:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7670"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59675"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"up